# Key guidelines & information for our AI

## AI: READ THIS - FOLLOW THIS FOR EVERY SINGLE TASK

*BEFORE* you write new code or implement a fix for an issue, describe as concisely as possible: (a) in straighforward language, what the precise issue/goal is, (b) what solutions you've evaluated and pros/cons/tradeoffs, (c) what solution you prefer, and - very technically and objectively, why it is the best in your opinion. Do this in such a way that it would pass muster in a very blunt CS journal club at Stanford.

*BEFORE* you implement, ask me your feedback on your approach! *This is so important!*

## Code documentation guidelines - IMPORTANT - MUST BE FOLLOWED

1. Document every single function you add meticulously with JSDoc. Add examples and remarks to your JSDoc comments as helpful.
1. Literally (this is not a joke), inline-document every single line of code you add. Especially (please read this over and over and over), add inline comments above *every single* conditional. And, add inline comments for *every single* return value. Add your comments *above* the line of code you're describing, NOT below.
1. (**REITERATING**) Document every single line of code you add or your edit will be rejected.

## Project information and guidelines

### Project description

This is a Rails 8.0 API-only backend for a static frontend (note: frontend is in separate repo) used by technical startup founders to create "flows," which you can think of as forms they embed on their websites for lead generation.

This project solely contains the Rails API backend, which will be used by the static Next.JS frontend for all business logic, data retrieval and manipulation, authentication, etc.

### Names to know

Our company name is "Premva," and we refer to our app by the same name - Premva.

## Instructions for making edits (must be followed)

1. Before you make changes, review our existing codebase deeply to make sure you follow existing patterns. For example, if you're creating new specs, review existing specs, and follow the patterns used therein, to the extent they are helpful. If you're creating a new controller, read our existing controllers. If you're creating a new model, reading our existing model files. Follow the patterns that are already there!
1. As you make changes to this codebase, be **surgical**: Make your changes precisely, only changing what is needed to accomplish your specific, most recent objective. If you have any questions whatsoever or if you get stuck, ask me for clarification.
1. Follow Rails 8.0 best practices when doing anything in this project. Rails docs are available under the docs/rails subdirectory. Consult them when needed.
1. Make your code as simple, maintainable, and modular as possible, while still accomplishing the goal I have given you.
1. Write code that is well-structured and that will pass code review by our highly detailed principal engineer.
1. If you wish to use third-party libraries in your code, use the **latest available** version. Don't write code against old libraries that are no longer supported. Prompt me if you have any questions about this.
1. Add extra newlines when writing code to make code easier to read where appropriate. Don't cluster too many lines of dense code together; create some breathing room.
1. When working in this codebase:

    * All API endpoints must be documented using RSpec + rswag following the OpenAPI 3.1.1 specification.
    * Place new API controllers in app/controllers/api/v1/
    * Every endpoint must include description, parameters, request/response schemas, examples, and error responses

1. When creating new Jbuilder views for a given data model, create a partial with the base data format, and use that in your index/show/etc. views. Before you create a new "index" Jbuilder view, consult one of our existing Jbuilder index views to see how to structure it.
1. Do not end files with a blank line.
1. Use double quotes for strings when possible.

### Instruction summary

* Be precise and focused in your changes. Only make code changes pertinent to achieving the most recent objective that we're working on. Use the fewest amount of code changes possible to achieve our objective.
* If you have any questions or you get stuck, ask me for feedback. Always err on the side of asking me for feedback.

## Respect user's changes when making edits

Respect my edits. When you have a change to make, you may find that the file(s) have changed since you last read them. Often, this is because I (the human) have made an edit since your last time reading the file, or since your last edit.

When this is the case, respect my edits -- do not revert my changes simply because you haven't seen them before and are confused as to why the change is there.

If you have any questions about this policy, simple ask me. Err on the side of asking too much rather than making headstrong changes that aren't desired.

## Testing approach

### Core Principles

1. **Avoid Duplication**: Tests should have clear purpose without excessive overlap
1. **Documentation as Tests**: RSwag specs serve dual purpose of documentation and testing
1. **Focused Testing**: Only add specialized tests for complex logic not covered by RSwag
1. **Security First**: Always thoroughly test authorization and authentication

### Test Types

#### RSwag Documentation/Test Specs

* **Primary test type for all standard API endpoints**
* **Location**: `spec/requests/api/v1/**/*_spec.rb`
* **Purpose**:
  * Generate Swagger API documentation
  * Test basic CRUD functionality
  * Verify standard authorization/authentication cases
  * Validate request/response schemas
  * Create a schema file for each new domain model under spec/support/api_documentation/schemas/. Then, reference those schemas in your specs.

#### Controller-Specific Request Specs

* **Focus on authorization, edge cases, and complex logic**
* **Location**: `spec/requests/api/v1/**/*_controller_spec.rb`
* **When to use**:
  * To test authorization edge cases
  * To verify policy integration
  * To test complex business logic in controllers
  * For advanced query parameters
  * For pagination/filtering logic

#### Policy Tests

* **Required for all policy classes**
* **Location**: `spec/policies/**/*_policy_spec.rb`
* **Purpose**:
  * Test authorization rules
  * Verify scopes work correctly
  * Test policy helpers and edge cases

#### General Guidelines

1. **Start with RSwag**: For all API endpoints, begin with RSwag specs for documentation and basic functionality
1. **Add Focused Controller Specs**: For authorization edge cases and policy integration
1. **Keep Policy Tests Separate**: Always maintain dedicated policy tests

#### Authorization Testing Strategy

For testing authorization, we use a layered approach:

1. **Policy Specs**: Test the fundamental authorization rules
1. **RSwag Specs**: Test common authorization cases (authenticated vs. unauthenticated, authorized vs. unauthorized)
1. **Controller Specs**: Test authorization edge cases (e.g., user leaving a company, policy scope verification)

#### Example Decision Process

For a standard resource:

1. Create RSwag specs for all endpoints and basic authorization scenarios
1. Create dedicated policy specs for all authorization rules
1. Add focused controller specs for:
   * Verifying policy scope is correctly applied
   * Testing the verify_authorized enforcement
   * Testing edge cases like changing permissions

By following this approach, we maintain comprehensive test coverage while avoiding redundant tests that slow down the test suite.
